"Act as an Expert Python full-stack developer. I need you to build a local Flask web application to automate the post-printing workflow for my Amazon e-commerce brand, Basa.
This app will process output print PDFs, ZIP them in a specific sorted order, and then parse, crop, sort, and reformat an uploaded Amazon packaging slip PDF to match that exact printing order.
Please write the complete, production-ready Flask application (app.py and HTML templates) using Flask, werkzeug, and PyMuPDF (fitz - crucial for text extraction, PDF cropping, and precise manipulation).
Phase 1: Upload & Sort Print PDFs
1. Input: The user uploads multiple print PDFs via the Flask web UI.
2. File Naming Conventions & ID Extraction:
Format: CustomerName-[4-Digit-ID][-Variant][-SpecialSuffix].pdf
Examples: Shahul-7788.pdf, shahul-1234&safrina-3456.pdf, Shahul-1352-1_2.pdf, shahul-1234-3x2.pdf.
Key Logic: Extract the first 4-digit number found after the first hyphen (e.g., 7788, 1234, 1352). This is the Last 4 Digits of the Amazon Order ID and will be used as the primary matching key later.
Note: If no variant (like 3x2, 3x3, 4x6) is in the name, it defaults to the 4x3 variant.
3. Strict Sorting Logic:
Sort the uploaded PDFs in this exact hierarchy:
Level 1 (By Variant): Order must be: 4x3 (default/no tag) -> 3x2 -> 3x3 -> 4x6.
Level 2 (By Complexity): Inside each variant group, place "Simple" names first (e.g., Shahul-7788.pdf). Place "Complex" names last (any file containing &, 1_2, 2_2, or set).
Level 3 (Alphabetical): Within the Simple and Complex groups, sort alphabetically by the Customer Name.
4. ZIP Creation:
Once sorted, rename the files in memory with a numerical prefix to enforce the sort order (e.g., 01_Shahul-7788.pdf). Package them into a single ZIP file named {Total_PDF_Count}board.zip and offer it for download.
Phase 2: Process & Match Amazon Packaging Slips
1. Input: The UI asks the user to upload their raw Amazon Packaging Slip PDF.
2. PDF Parsing & ID Matching:
Iterate through the Amazon PDF using PyMuPDF.
Search the text for the phrase "Order Id: ". It will look like Order Id: 171-0259567-3946733.
Extract the last four digits of that full order ID (e.g., 6733).
Compare these 4 digits against the sorted list of print PDFs from Phase 1.
3. Cropping & Deduplication (Crucial Step):
The Amazon PDF often contains BOTH the Shipping Label (with barcodes and the text 'ATSPL') and the Tax Invoice on the same page.
Use PyMuPDF to calculate the bounding box of just the Shipping Label portion (look for the area containing the barcodes, "Order Id:", and "ATSPL"). Use page.set_cropbox() or page rendering to isolate ONLY the shipping label, discarding the Tax Invoice half.
Deduplication: Print PDFs might share the same Order ID (e.g., shahul-1352-1_2.pdf and shahul-1352-2_2.pdf). Keep ONLY ONE cropped shipping label per unique 4-digit Order ID. Discard duplicates.
Sort these final cropped labels to perfectly match the sequence of the sorted print PDFs.
4. Stamping Serial Numbers:
Iterate through the sorted, cropped packing slips.
Use PyMuPDF to stamp a sequential serial number (1, 2, 3...) onto the label.
Placement: Bottom-right area of the shipping label, near the text 'ATSPL'. Make it a highly visible, bold font.
5. Generating the 4-Up A4 Layout:
Create a new, blank A4 PDF document (595 x 842 points).
Take the sorted, stamped, cropped shipping labels and place them 4-per-page onto the A4 document.
Layout Order per A4 page: Top-Left (1), Top-Right (2), Bottom-Left (3), Bottom-Right (4). Scale the label dimensions as necessary to fit this 2x2 grid without distorting the aspect ratio.
6. Final Output: Offer this final, 4-up A4 PDF for download.
Please provide the full app.py script, modularizing the sorting, regex matching, and PDF manipulation logic into clear functions. Include inline comments explaining the PyMuPDF coordinates, regex patterns for the 4-digit ID extraction, and the cropping logic. Provide the basic index.html template to handle the multi-step UI."
